==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germain ''*gastiz'', from Indo-European ''*gʰostis'' ‘guest, stranger’.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[gast]] (Dutch [[gast]]), Old High German [[gast]] (German [[Gast]]), Old Norse [[gestr]] (Swedish [[gäst]]), Gothic [[𐌲𐌰𐍃𐍄𐍃]] ‘stranger’.  The Indo-European root is also the source of Latin [[hostis]], Old Church Slavonic [[гость]] (Russian [[гость]]).

